{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567289"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:58:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:58:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18955"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18955"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.21,0.49,0.11,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11689"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115417"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11689"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18955"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97420"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2650"},{"type":"tags","id":"2774"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27502"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43712"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47832"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47842"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115417"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 79-year-old man is admitted to hospital following a fall at home. He was found confused with a capillary blood glucose of 2.8 mmol/L (3.9-7.8). He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes, hypertension, atrial fibrillation, heart failure, chronic kidney disease (estimated glomerular filtration rate 45 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2), osteoarthritis, and depression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medications include metformin 1000 mg twice daily, gliclazide modified release 60 mg daily, sitagliptin 50 mg daily, perindopril, bisoprolol, apixaban, furosemide, duloxetine, paracetamol, and cholecalciferol. His most recent glycated haemoglobin (HbA1c) was 8.2% (4.0-6.0) three months ago. He reports difficulty managing his multiple daily medications and often forgets his evening doses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears frail but has recovered from his hypoglycaemic episode. His vital signs are within normal limits. He has reduced grip strength and walks with a frame.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate principle for managing his diabetes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Add empagliflozin to improve glycemic control and reduce cardiovascular risk","Cease gliclazide and commence linagliptin","Simplify regimen to once-daily medications with relaxed targets","Initiate basal insulin to improve glycaemic control","Continue current medications with increased monitoring"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case illustrates the challenges of managing diabetes in a frail older adult with multiple comorbidities and polypharmacy. The patient\u0027s presentation with hypoglycaemia, difficulty managing medications, and evidence of frailty (reduced grip strength, use of frame) suggests that his current regimen is too complex and potentially harmful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimplifying the regimen to once-daily medications with relaxed targets\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate approach. Guidelines recommend less stringent HbA1c targets (7.5-8.5%) for frail older adults to prioritise quality of life and avoid adverse events. His current HbA1c of 8.2% is actually within this acceptable range for his age and comorbidities. Simplification could involve continuing metformin (possibly at a reduced dose or once daily formulation) while considering discontinuing medications that increase hypoglycaemia risk such as gliclazide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeasing gliclazide \u003C/strong\u003Ereduces the risk of hypoglycaemia through ceasing sulfonylurea and is a reasonable approach, but \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommencing linagliptin \u003C/strong\u003Eis not necessary unless glycaemic control cannot be attained on a simpler regimen. This option alone doesn\u0027t fully address the need for a comprehensive approach to medication management with consideration of relaxed targets and overall medication burden.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdding empagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as it would increase regimen complexity and introduce new risks. While sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 inhibitors have cardiovascular benefits, the risks (volume depletion, falls, urinary tract infections) outweigh potential benefits in this frail patient with chronic kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiating basal insulin\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as it would significantly increase both regimen complexity and hypoglycaemia risk. This would be particularly problematic given his demonstrated difficulty managing current oral medications and recent hypoglycaemic episode.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuing current medications with increased monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E fails to address the fundamental issues of medication burden and risk. Simply monitoring more closely without making changes to reduce risk is not an appropriate strategy in a patient who has already experienced a serious adverse event.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In older adults with multiple comorbidities, less stringent glycaemic targets (HbA1c 7.5-8.5%) are appropriate to reduce risk of hypoglycaemia.","Medication simplification and de-prescribing are key principles in managing polypharmacy in older adults.","Quality of life and patient preferences should be prioritised over strict disease control in frail elderly patients."],"references":["Hoel RW, Giddings Connolly RM, Takahashi PY. Polypharmacy Management in Older Patients. Mayo Clin Proc. 2021;96(1):242-256. doi:10.1016/j.mayocp.2020.06.012. Available online at ; https://www.mayoclinicproceedings.org/article/S0025-6196(20)30616-9/fulltext","NDSS. AUSTRALIAN TYPE 2 DIABETES GLYCAEMIC MANAGEMENT ALGORITHM. Racgp. [Internet]. Accessed on 7 May 2025. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/63ef724a-cac8-4be5-908d-9c544a543d3d/Australian-type-2-diabetes-management-algorithm-June-2024.pdf.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97420"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18955"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97420"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T16:55:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T16:56:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11689"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115417"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","na